If you are looking to earn passive income and are willing to take a little extra risk and diversify your investments then P2P lending platforms can give you what you want. Usually banks take money from you and lend it to borrowers, but on a P2P platform you can directly lend money to such borrowers and earn an average return of 12-18% unlike the 2-6% returns you earn on bank depoosits. Although the borrowers are segregated based on their risk profiles and credit rating, P2P investments are a little high risk since borrowers may not repay their loans as agreed, leading to losses for lenders. 
Nonetheless, it is the duty of the P2P platform operators to follow all the legal steps to recover the money. Moreover, your money as an investor/ lender is divided in multiple loan accounts which can be as small as one rupee, so the risk of default is also managed effectively.
Plus, you can start P2P investments with as small as 500 rupee so why not give it a try?

[P2P, investment, finance, RBI]

Before you buy medical insurance make sure you are clear on the claim reimbursement process. Basically there are 2 types of reimbursement process: one being cashless where as a patient you do not have to pay any amount and one being the reimbursement process where initially the entire bill is paid by you and later the amount is reimbursed by your insurance provider provided they are satisfied with the documents.

A cashless reimbursement could also have a co-payment sub clause in it, whereby an agreed percentage of the bill say 10% will have to be paid by you (which is also reimbursable later) and the balance is settled directly between the insurance provider and hospital)

A cashless claim offers you immediate treatment without worrying for arranging the money, is hassle-free and keeps you protected incase of emergencies and travels.

So call your agent today and ensure you are safe!

[finance, insurance, mediclaim]

Credit card companies will always offer you a credit limit higher than your monthly income, but not all the limit is meant for you to use.

So if you want to maintain a healthy credit score, you must not utilise more than 30-40% of your average credit limit. And that’s because if you increase your credit usage it implies that you have poor money management skills, which makes you a risky customer, thus decreasing your credit score.

And if you still don’t know why it is imperative to maintain a healthy credit score, I suggest you hit the follow button right away 😌

[finance, banks, credit card, credit score]

Worried that higher credit utilisation will bring down your credit score? Well, don’t worry because I’ve got your covered.

In case of higher credit utilisation in any month you can simply pay a major sum of the bill before the statement is generated and bring down your utilisation under 30% thereby keeping your credit score safe.
